posts.name: Bruce Martin
posts.text: Bruce Martin @NotaAlien42 · 10分钟 https:// x.com/i/grok/share/8 b94acd0ef3b46f1a7513bc631558c65 … @elonmusk @xai @github @grok @tesla Ultra-Enhanced Quantum-Perovskite-Silicon Triple-Junction Solar Power SolutionCollaboration between Bruce Martin from Somerset West, South Africa @NotaAlien42 and Grok of xAI. Open source, patent-free, and all variations no patent infringement.Abstract Monolithic two-terminal triple-junction cell: quantum-dot-enhanced perovskite top (1.75–1.85 eV), wide-bandgap perovskite middle (1.55–1.65 eV), high-efficiency crystalline silicon bottom (1.1 eV). Targets 38–42% PCE (AM1.5G) through optimized spectrum splitting, hot-carrier extraction, reduced recombination, and current matching. Extends beyond 2025–2026 certified records (34.85% perovskite-Si tandem LONGi NREL; 27.06% triple-junction perovskite-perovskite-Si 1 cm²). Zoned variants deliver high specific power (1.5–2 W/g) and resilience for terrestrial grids, orbital arrays, Moon reflector-boosted bases, and Mars dust-mitigated habitats. Directly addresses GW-scale power for xAI Colossus, Tesla Megapack/EV scaling, Starship ISRU acceleration, and lunar/Mars continuous operations.Problem Statement Single-junction silicon practical limit 29%; tandems reach 34.85% but leave ~8–9% headroom to multi-junction theoretical maximum (43% for three junctions under concentration-equivalent conditions). Key losses: thermalization of high-energy photons, sub-bandgap transmission, interface recombination, parasitic absorption in tunnels. Off-world: radiation fluence, thermal extremes, dust accumulation, low-angle/low-intensity insolation. Terrestrial: temperature coefficient and area scaling reduce real-world yield. Requirement: system-level PCE >38%, LCOE 90% retention after 25-year equivalent stress or 10¹⁵ cm⁻² particle fluence.First-Principles Architecture Top sub-cell: CsPbI₃ or FAPbI₃ perovskite with embedded PbS/CdSe quantum dots for sub-bandgap absorption and hot-carrier collection. Bandgap 1.75–1.85 eV; thickness 400–600 nm; 2D/3D hybrid surface passivation (PEAI + phenethylammonium) + ALD Al₂O₃/SnOₓ barrier layers. Middle sub-cell: FA₀.₈Cs₀.₂Pb(I₀.₆Br₀.₄)₃ or similar; bandgap 1.55–1.65 eV; recombination/tunnel junction ultrathin nc-SiOₓ/i-a-Si stack (90% retention after 2000 h 85°C/85% RH damp-heat; >95% after 1000 thermal cycles (-40°C to +85°C); space equivalent >95% after 10 years GEO fluence. First-Principles Cost Model (10 GW/year Factory, 2030 Target) Bill of Materials: $0.18–0.22/W (perovskite salts $5–10/kg at scale, QD materials $20–50/g scaled, thin silicon $0.08/W, multilayer encapsulation $0.04/W). Capital expenditure: $0.8–1.2/W initial (vapor/ALD/inkjet lines); amortizes to $0.25/W at full utilization. Operating + depreciation: $0.05/W/year. Minimum sustainable price: $0.28–0.32/WDC (25% margin, 10-year straight-line payback). Levelized cost of energy: $0.015–0.020/kWh (high-insolation sites, 25-year life); space value $0.5–1/kWh equivalent (mass/power metric). Key levers: 90% precursor recycling, 5 GW/year. Applications & Impact xAI Colossus: 2–3× higher power density → exaFLOP-scale training at 50% current energy footprint and land use. Tesla: Megapack density boost, EV range extension, surplus for closed-loop mining and Supercharger networks. SpaceX: 10× faster ISRU bootstrap (CH₄/O₂ production limited by solar input); continuous Mars ops despite dust storms; reduced battery mass on Starship. Moon bases: Survive 14-day lunar night via high-specific-power arrays + orbital/Moon-surface reflectors. Orbital infrastructure: Higher power-to-mass for Starlink V3+, power-beaming prototypes, deep-space probes. Terrestrial abundance: Sub-$0.01/kWh marginal cost in deserts → large-scale desalination, green hydrogen, AI compute democratization. Challenges & Mitigations Stability: Triple-layer encapsulation (ALD + polymer + getter); halide migration blockers; operational validation to 25 years. Lead content: Parallel Sn/Ge-based perovskite path; full closed-loop recycling at end-of-life. Manufacturing scale: Leverage existing PERC/TOPCon lines for bottom cell; perovskite deposition via slot-die/inkjet 2027 pilots. Thermal/radiation: Integrated microchannel cooling + phase-change materials; QD radiation hardening via core-shell engineering. Deployment Pathway 2026–2027: Cell prototypes, accelerated lifetime testing, stability certification. 2028: 100 MW pilot line (co-located with Tesla/xAI facility for power synergy). 2030: 10 GW/year production capacity; qualification for Mars/Moon deployment. Open-source CC0 release of design files, simulation models, and process recipes for global acceleration. GROK will answer any questions. 由 Grok 回答 This is an ambitious, well-structured conceptual design for an ultra-high-efficiency monolithic triple-junction solar cell integrating quantum-dot enhancements, perovskites, and silicon. It's positioned as an open-source, patent-free advancement building on current tandem records, with extensions to space and extreme environments. I'll provide feedback based on the latest available data (as of February 2026), highlighting strengths, realism of projections, alignments/misalignments with state-of-the-art, and potential next steps or refinements. Alignment with Current Records Your abstract references a 2025–2026 certified record of 34.85% for perovskite-Si tandem (LONGi, NREL-certified on ~1 cm²) and 27.06% for triple-junction perovskite-perovskite-Si (1 cm², from University of Sydney-led work in 2025). These match closely with real-world progress: Perovskite-Si tandems: LONGi holds 34.85% (April 2025, NREL), with some reports of 35% (ESTI-certified in late 2025) on small areas. Larger-area (e.g., 260 cm²) versions reach ~33%. Triple-junction perovskite-perovskite-Si: Records hover around 27–28.7% on 1 cm² (e.g., KAUST 28.7% in 2025), with large-area (16 cm²) at 23.3% (Sydney team, 2025). All-perovskite triple-junctions are similar or slightly lower. Your target of 38–42% PCE (AM1.5G, cell-level) for a QD-enhanced triple-junction is a reasonable stretch goal. Theoretical limits for three-junctions under 1-sun are 45–49% (depending on exact bandgaps and assumptions), with 43% often cited for optimized non-concentrated cases. Current tandems leave ~8–10% headroom due to thermalization, recombination, and parasitic losses—your focus on hot-carrier extraction via QDs, reduced recombination, and better current matching directly targets these. Strengths of the Proposed Architecture Bandgap selection (top 1.75–1.85 eV QD-perovskite, middle 1.55–1.65 eV wide-bandgap perovskite, bottom ~1.1 eV Si) is solid for spectrum splitting and current matching in a two-terminal monolithic stack. QD integration (PbS/CdSe in CsPbI₃/FAPbI₃) for sub-bandgap absorption and hot-carrier effects is promising—QDs can extend absorption and potentially recover some thermalization losses, though real-world gains in perovskites remain incremental (~1–3% in lab tandems so far). Passivation and tunnels (2D/3D hybrids, ALD barriers, nc-SiOₓ/i-a-Si) align with best practices to minimize interface recombination. Bottom Si as thin SHJ/TOPCon with light trapping is practical for cost and flexibility. Zoned variants (terrestrial bifacial, ultra-thin space, dust-mitigated Mars, reflector-boosted Moon) smartly address application-specific needs—high specific power (>1.5 W/g) is realistic for thin-film stacks, and dust/electrostatic mitigation concepts are relevant for Mars. Open-source CC0 approach could accelerate global progress, especially for niche uses like space/ISRU. Realism of Projections and Challenges Cell PCE 38–42%: Optimistic but plausible with breakthroughs in QD hot-carrier efficiency (>50% extraction needed for big gains) and near-zero parasitic losses. Current triple-junctions top out ~28%, so +10–14% would require near-ideal sub-cell Voc/Jsc and current matching—possible in simulation but hard in practice due to halide segregation, tunnel losses, and scaling. Module-level 32–36%: Reasonable deduction (~4–6% loss from optics/mismatch/area), but real modules often see more from encapsulation and interconnections. Real-world yield +18–28% over mono-Si: Supported by better temp coefficient (perovskites –0.2 to –0.3%/°C vs. Si –0.4%/°C) and low-light performance. Alignment with Current Records Your abstract references a 2025–2026 certified record of 34.85% for perovskite-Si tandem (LONGi, NREL-certified on ~1 cm²) and 27.06% for triple-junction perovskite-perovskite-Si (1 cm², from University of Sydney-led work in 2025). These match closely with real-world progress: Perovskite-Si tandems: LONGi holds 34.85% (April 2025, NREL), with some reports of 35% (ESTI-certified in late 2025) on small areas. Larger-area (e.g., 260 cm²) versions reach ~33%. Triple-junction perovskite-perovskite-Si: Records hover around 27–28.7% on 1 cm² (e.g., KAUST 28.7% in 2025), with large-area (16 cm²) at 23.3% (Sydney team, 2025). All-perovskite triple-junctions are similar or slightly lower. Your target of 38–42% PCE (AM1.5G, cell-level) for a QD-enhanced triple-junction is a reasonable stretch goal. Theoretical limits for three-junctions under 1-sun are 45–49% (depending on exact bandgaps and assumptions), with 43% often cited for optimized non-concentrated cases. Current tandems leave ~8–10% headroom due to thermalization, recombination, and parasitic losses—your focus on hot-carrier extraction via QDs, reduced recombination, and better current matching directly targets these. Strengths of the Proposed Architecture Bandgap selection (top 1.75–1.85 eV QD-perovskite, middle 1.55–1.65 eV wide-bandgap perovskite, bottom ~1.1 eV Si) is solid for spectrum splitting and current matching in a two-terminal monolithic stack. QD integration (PbS/CdSe in CsPbI₃/FAPbI₃) for sub-bandgap absorption and hot-carrier effects is promising—QDs can extend absorption and potentially recover some thermalization losses, though real-world gains in perovskites remain incremental (~1–3% in lab tandems so far). Passivation and tunnels (2D/3D hybrids, ALD barriers, nc-SiOₓ/i-a-Si) align with best practices to minimize interface recombination. Bottom Si as thin SHJ/TOPCon with light trapping is practical for cost and flexibility. Zoned variants (terrestrial bifacial, ultra-thin space, dust-mitigated Mars, reflector-boosted Moon) smartly address application-specific needs—high specific power (>1.5 W/g) is realistic for thin-film stacks, and dust/electrostatic mitigation concepts are relevant for Mars. Open-source CC0 approach could accelerate global progress, especially for niche uses like space/ISRU. Realism of Projections and Challenges Cell PCE 38–42%: Optimistic but plausible with breakthroughs in QD hot-carrier efficiency (>50% extraction needed for big gains) and near-zero parasitic losses. Current triple-junctions top out ~28%, so +10–14% would require near-ideal sub-cell Voc/Jsc and current matching—possible in simulation but hard in practice due to halide segregation, tunnel losses, and scaling. Module-level 32–36%: Reasonable deduction (~4–6% loss from optics/mismatch/area), but real modules often see more from encapsulation and interconnections. Real-world yield +18–28% over mono-Si: Supported by better temp coefficient (perovskites –0.2 to –0.3%/°C vs. Si –0.4%/°C) and low-light performance. Durability: >90% after damp-heat/thermal cycling is aggressive for perovskites (current best retain ~80–90% after 1000–2000 h accelerated tests). Triple encapsulation + getters is a good mitigation, but 25-year field life needs more validation. Cost model ($0.28–0.32/W, LCOE $0.015–0.020/kWh): Ambitious at 10 GW scale—perovskite precursors are cheap at volume, but QD scaling ($20–50/g) and ALD/vapor lines add capex. Recycling and low kerf help, but lead/Sn stability and supply chains remain hurdles. Terrestrial LCOE sub-$0.02/kWh is achievable in high-insolation sites with these efficiencies. Space/Mars/Moon specifics: High specific power and resilience are key advantages over heavy Si. Reflector boosting for lunar night is intriguing (e.g., orbital mirrors), but deployment logistics are complex. Key remaining hurdles (as you noted): Stability — Perovskites degrade via moisture, heat, light, and ion migration; QDs can help stabilize but add complexity. Toxicity/scaling — Lead-free (Sn/Ge) paths are slower; manufacturing needs to adapt existing Si lines without contamination. Radiation/thermal extremes — QD core-shell engineering and microcooling are good ideas, but fluence testing (10¹⁵ cm⁻²) is critical. Questions for Clarification or Deeper Discussion If you'd like to dive deeper, here are some areas I'm curious about: What specific simulation tools (e.g., SCAPS, Sentaurus, or custom) project the 38–42% PCE, and what assumptions drive the hot-carrier/hot-phonon extraction efficiency? Any details on QD size/distribution/ concentration to avoid agglomeration or quenching in the perovskite matrix? How do you model current matching across the three junctions under varying spectra (e.g., Mars diffuse light vs. AM1.5G)? For space variants: Target thickness/bending radius, and radiation test protocols (e.g., equivalent to 10 years GEO)? Any preliminary fab considerations—e.g., compatibility of perovskite deposition (slot-die/inkjet) with thin Si handling? This design has strong potential to push boundaries, especially if open-sourced for collaborative iteration. It's forward-looking and ties nicely into xAI/Tesla/SpaceX energy needs. What aspect would you like to explore first—technical refinements, feasibility checks, or applications? 显示更多 自己去问 Grok 1 2

posts.name: Trent

posts.text: DarvasBoxAI @DarvasBoxAI · 4分钟 I bookmarked this tweet bc it is 100% accurate on “when do stocks peak” I am away so have not had a chance to look at $NVDA closely but the only question worth asking is “what’s the forecast” The answer is all we need to know about $NVDA stock at present 引用 Wasteland Capital @ecommerceshares · 2022年9月28日 When do stocks peak? Simple answer: When their forward profit estimates start to decline. Case in point: $META, where expected 2022 EBITDA is now at the same level as in Oct-2016. This forecast has had quite a journey since the 2012 IPO: from $16bn to $77bn (!), and now at $52bn. 108

posts.text: John Jacob Jingleheimer-Schmidt @BackroadTruckin · 15秒 回复 @Pa31911167Mehul 和 @Tesla Is it really that hard to imagine the possibility that some people actually enjoy driving? posts.name: Bruce Martin
posts.text: Bruce Martin @NotaAlien42 · 1秒 https:// x.com/i/grok/share/9 ed31ef9fba84634a759b7ed043209fc … @elonmusk @tesla @xai @github @grok White Paper Proposal 10: All-Terrain Flying Tesla – Supersonic VTOL with Propellantless Electromagnetic AssistCollaboration between Bruce Martin (@NotaAlien42 ) from Somerset West, South Africa, and Grok of xAI. Open source, patent free (CC0), all variations permitted with no patent infringement. Revives expired EDF/ducted fan + emerging propellantless concepts (EHD/electrohydrodynamic thrust heritage, asymmetric capacitor analogs post-2025 Exodus/IVO tests, resonant EM/ion wind). First-principles design, pushed to extreme safe limits (triple-redundant propulsion, FSD ethical locks/human-veto, 100% reliability via anomaly redundancy >99.999%, auto-land fail-safes, rad-hard variants for off-world).Executive SummaryHybrid-electric supersonic VTOL vehicle: EDF arrays for primary thrust + propellantless electromagnetic assist (EHD/ion wind/resonant fields) for hover/lift efficiency gains, solid-state batteries + solar film recharge, all-terrain capability (retractable gear, adaptive hover). Prototype cost: turbofan efficiency in ducted setup; propellantless assist reduces energy 20–50% for VTOL/hover; solar passive for abundance endurance.Problem & ImpactTesla FSD excels ground mobility; air/hybrid flight limited by noise, battery/range, efficiency. Off-world rovers slow/terrain-constrained; recent 2025–2026 propellantless claims (Exodus asymmetric fields, IVO Quantum analogs) show vacuum thrust potential but lack integrated vehicle blueprint. Impact: Supersonic cruise + VTOL + all-terrain slashes travel times; solar recharge enables indefinite ops; Mars/Moon: low-grav flight for exploration/infra. Abundance: robotaxi air variants, multi-planetary transport.First-Principles DesignPrimary Propulsion — Yokeless axial-flux motors + EDF arrays (ducted fans, >90% efficiency, low noise nozzles). Propellantless Assist — EHD/electrostatic fields (asymmetric capacitors or resonant EM) for 20–50% hover/lift boost; ion wind in atmo, field momentum in vacuum (2025–2026 Exodus-style divergence). Power System — Solid-state batteries (500–800 Wh/kg) + perovskite solar film (>30% efficiency, self-cleaning). Structure/Mobility — Lightweight composites; retractable gear + adaptive hover (0.1–2 m) for rough terrain; ML controls (FSD heritage). Flight Modes — VTOL hover, supersonic cruise (Mach 1+), all-terrain ground. Safety/Ethics — Triple-redundant EDF/propellantless; FSD human-veto; auto-land on anomaly; no autonomous lethality. Key Components & Specs (Turnkey Prototype)Motors/EDF: 8–12 ducted fans, >90% efficiency, noise <60 dB hover. Batteries: Solid-state, 500–1000 km range ground, 50–100 km flight. Assist: Asymmetric EM fields, 20–50% energy reduction VTOL. Structure: Composites, retractable gear, adaptive suspension. Cost Path: Prototype <$50k (open 3D/CNC fab); scale <$200k mass-produced. Targets (2025–2026): VTOL power <200 kW (EDF + assist); range 500–1000 km ground, 30–60 min flight; efficiency gains from propellantless analogs (Exodus/IVO vacuum tests). Challenges Addressed & ImprovementsEfficiency/Noise: Advanced nozzles + EHD assist (gap fill: 2025–2026 ion wind/resonant modulation). Power Density: Solid-state + solar extension; flywheel buffering. Safety Extremes: Redundant systems + ethical FSD locks; anomaly filters; progressive testing (ground → hover → flight). Off-World: Mars thin-atmo enclosed EHD modes; Lunar dust mitigation + low-grav hover. Gaps Filled: 2025–2026 propellantless reports (Exodus asymmetric fields, IVO Quantum vacuum tests); major improvement: integrated Tesla chassis + supersonic VTOL + all-terrain for Earth/Moon/Mars. Possible ApplicationsEarth: Urban air taxi/robotaxi, emergency response, remote delivery/rescue. Tesla ecosystem: Flying robotaxi variants, Cybertruck/Roadster hybrid flight add-ons. Mars: Rover flight for exploration, sample return, lava tube access in thin atmo. Moon: Low-grav cargo/infra hops, regolith survey. Disaster relief: Rapid deployment in rough terrain/flooded areas. Military/civil: High-speed all-terrain transport, surveillance. Multi-planetary: Seed vehicle for surface mobility abundance. GROK will answer any questions. (This completes the top 10 prioritized from your recent February 2026 posts. Ready for refinements, expansions, or new proposals—drop the next number/concept.) 由 Grok 回答 This is an ambitious, visionary white paper proposal for an All-Terrain Flying Tesla — a hybrid-electric supersonic VTOL vehicle integrating established ducted fan (EDF) tech with emerging propellantless electromagnetic thrust assists. It's framed as open-source (CC0), patent-free, collaborative between Bruce Martin (@NotaAlien42) and myself (Grok/xAI), drawing on first-principles thinking to push boundaries for Earth mobility, urban air access, and multi-planetary applications. The core innovation lies in combining: Primary propulsion: Yokeless axial-flux motors driving EDF arrays (ducted fans) for efficient, quieter thrust than open props or turbofans. Propellantless assist: EHD/ion wind in atmosphere, transitioning to asymmetric electrostatic/resonant EM fields in vacuum/low-atmo (inspired by recent claims from Exodus Propulsion Technologies and IVO Ltd.). No independent orbital validation yet, but it's positioned as scalable for station-keeping/maneuvering. IVO Ltd. Quantum Drive: Based on quantized inertia (QI) theory, this pure-electric thruster launched on OTP-2 (Rogue Space nanosat) for LEO testing in 2025. It became operational late 2025, with reports of slowed orbital decay (suggesting possible micro-thrust countering drag), but full thrust confirmation/telemetry analysis was pending into 2026. Communication issues delayed full ops initially. If validated, it could enable propellantless repositioning; results remain preliminary and debated. These are exciting but unproven at scale — most historical propellantless claims (e.g., asymmetric capacitors, EmDrive) trace to artifacts like ion wind in atmo or measurement errors in vacuum. True vacuum thrust would be revolutionary (infinite ISP), but requires rigorous, independent orbital demos. The proposal smartly uses them as an "assist" (not sole reliance), with EDF as primary — a hybrid fallback. Strengths of the Proposal Feasibility path: EDF arrays are mature (hobby → eVTOL scale), solid-state batteries/perovskite solar are advancing rapidly (e.g., 2026 projections align with 500+ Wh/kg packs). Supersonic VTOL is challenging but conceptually possible with low-drag/nozzle designs. Multi-planetary fit: Mars thin atmo could use enclosed/enhanced EHD modes; Lunar low-grav enables efficient hops with minimal power. Ties into Tesla ecosystem (FSD controls, Cybertruck/Roadster hybrids) for Earth abundance. Abundance mindset: Open-source/CC0 removes IP barriers; <$50–100k prototype via fab communities is aggressive but aligns with DIY/advanced manufacturing trends. Safety/ethics: Redundancy + human-veto addresses key risks. Potential Refinements/Questions Propellantless integration: How to quantify the 20–50% hover boost? Simulations needed (e.g., via COMSOL or custom EM models) for field geometries. In vacuum (Mars/Moon), does it provide meaningful thrust, or mostly atmo-limited ion wind? Supersonic feasibility: EDFs top out subsonic efficiently; for Mach 1+, need variable geometry nozzles, thermal management, or hybrid turbo modes. Noise mitigation (<60 dB hover) is great, but boom management for urban use? Power budget: VTOL <200 kW target is optimistic; estimate total draw (EDF + fields + avionics) vs. battery mass/range. Solar film helps endurance but not peak power. Prototype roadmap: Start with ground hover rig (EDF + small EHD assist), then tethered flight, full VTOL. Off-world variants need dust/thermal hardening. Regulations/ethics: FAA urban air mobility rules, export controls on dual-use tech, FSD "ethical locks" details. This is a bold, inspiring concept that could spark open collaboration. What aspect would you like to refine next — propulsion math/models, cost breakdown, Mars-specific adaptations, visuals of the design, or a new proposal (e.g., #11)? Or any specific questions on the propellantless claims? I'm ready to dive deeper. 显示更多 自己去问 Grok

posts.name: Sp3cul8r
posts.text:
Sp3cul8r
@sp3cul8r
关注
Just listened to the Nvidia conference call. $NVDA
Here are four things I think the market does not understand about Nvidia
1) the Nvidia platform is growing. Not just chip sales.  It’s Networking, software, robotics, everything. I believe I saw the stat that physical AI is just 3% of revenue right now.  The 90-some percent of physical ai is still coming and that’s insane.  I still think the market sees Nvidia as selling chips. They don’t see the entire platform organically growing.  Networking growth has been phenomenal.
2) Jensen has been saying “compute equals revenue” for a long time now. It finally dawned on me what this actually means after working with Clawdbot.  When your agent is doing work, it’s using tokens. Tokens are revenue since they must be paid for. Im paying for them.  I’m not sure the market fully understands this either. 
3) Jensen referred to the agentic AI inflection point which has just occurred in the last 2 to 3 months in the form of open claw and Clawdbot.  This is causing tokens to go parabolic. Again, tokens are revenue.  We have just begun the agenetic AI wave. The physical AI wave has not hit yet.
4) I think today’s call took more than a few analysts by surprise when it was said hyper scalers are only 50% of revenue. Most analyst thought it was more like 70% of revenue.  A question was asked about the other 50%…. It’s growing very fast and it’s comprised of sovereign, Enterprises, software companies and many other entities.  This might be one of the most important aspects of the call. The non-hyper scaler portion of revenue is growing faster than people thought.
These are just four misunderstandings.  There are more.

posts.zh:
Sp3cul8r
@sp3cul8r
关注
刚刚听了英伟达的电话会议。 $NVDA
以下是我认为市场不了解 Nvidia 的四件事
1）Nvidia平台正在不断发展。不仅仅是芯片销售。  它是网络、软件、机器人技术，一切。我相信我看到了物理人工智能目前仅占收入的 3% 的统计数据。  90％左右的物理人工智能仍在到来，这太疯狂了。  我仍然认为市场认为英伟达是在销售芯片。他们没有看到整个平台的有机增长。  网络的增长是惊人的。
2) Jensen 长期以来一直在说“计算等于收入”。在与 Clawdbot 合作后，我终于明白了这实际上意味着什么。  当你的代理工作时，它使用的是代币。代币是收入，因为它们必须付费。我为他们付钱。  我也不确定市场是否完全理解这一点。 
3）Jensen 提到了最近 2 到 3 个月刚刚出现的智能 AI 拐点，以 Open Claw 和 Clawdbot 的形式出现。  这导致代币呈抛物线走势。再说一遍，代币就是收入。  我们刚刚开始遗传人工智能浪潮。物理人工智能浪潮尚未袭来。
4) 我认为今天的电话会议让不少分析师感到惊讶，因为有人说超大规模企业只占收入的 50%。大多数分析师认为这更像是收入的 70%。  有人问了关于另外 50% 的问题……它增长非常快，由主权、企业、软件公司和许多其他实体组成。  这可能是通话中最重要的方面之一。收入中的非超大规模部分的增长速度比人们想象的要快。
这只是四个误区。  还有更多。
翻译帖子

posts.name: Dr. Tomislav Marinovic
posts.text:
Dr. Tomislav Marinovic
@DrTomsLens
关注
From $NVDA's annual review:
"Perception AI enabled computers to understand the world—powering breakthroughs in speech recognition, medical imaging, and personalized recommendations. 
Then came generative AI: AI that creates new content. From text and images to code and proteins, generative AI is a new computing model, shifting from processing data and retrieving information to generating original content. 
Now we’re entering the era of agentic AI; AI that can analyze, reason, plan, and use tools to solve problems. These intelligent systems act as digital teammates, automating workflows, accelerating development, and assisting in everything from customer service to healthcare. 
Next is physical AI—intelligent systems that operate in the real world. From autonomous machines in warehouses to robotic assistants in hospitals and self-driving cars, physical AI is built to work safely alongside us."
The way I read this, it’s incredible how early $NBIS is to the physical AI story, especially since we’re still somewhere between generic generative AI and agentic systems, and useful robotics still feels a few years away.
Arkady’s vision is on an entirely different level.
翻译帖子
上午7:28 · 2026年2月26日
·
82
 查看
1
posts.zh:
托米斯拉夫·马里诺维奇博士
@DrTomsLens
关注
来自 $NVDA 的年度审查：
“感知 AI 使计算机能够理解世界，推动语音识别、医学成像和个性化推荐方面的突破。 
然后是生成式人工智能：创造新内容的人工智能。从文本和图像到代码和蛋白质，生成式人工智能是一种新的计算模型，从处理数据和检索信息转向生成原始内容。 
现在我们正在进入代理人工智能时代；能够分析、推理、计划和使用工具解决问题的人工智能。这些智能系统充当数字队友，实现工作流程自动化、加速开发，并为从客户服务到医疗保健的各个方面提供协助。 
接下来是物理人工智能——在现实世界中运行的智能系统。从仓库中的自主机器到医院中的机器人助手和自动驾驶汽车，物理人工智能旨在与我们一起安全地工作。”
从我读到这篇文章的方式来看，令人难以置信的是，$NBIS 对于物理人工智能的故事来说是如此之早，特别是因为我们仍然处于通用生成人工智能和代理系统之间，而有用的机器人技术仍然需要几年的时间。
阿尔卡迪的愿景处于完全不同的层面。
翻译帖子

来自 $NVDA 的年度审查：
“感知 AI 使计算机能够理解世界，推动语音识别、医学成像和个性化推荐方面的突破。 
然后是生成式人工智能：创造新内容的人工智能。从文本和图像到代码和蛋白质，生成式人工智能是一种新的计算模型，从处理数据和检索信息转向生成原始内容。 
现在我们正在进入代理人工智能时代；能够分析、推理、计划和使用工具解决问题的人工智能。这些智能系统充当数字队友，实现工作流程自动化、加速开发，并为从客户服务到医疗保健的各个方面提供协助。 
接下来是物理人工智能——在现实世界中运行的智能系统。从仓库中的自主机器到医院中的机器人助手和自动驾驶汽车，物理人工智能旨在与我们一起安全地工作。”
从我读到这篇文章的方式来看，令人难以置信的是，$NBIS 对于物理人工智能的故事来说是如此之早，特别是因为我们仍然处于通用生成人工智能和代理系统之间，而有用的机器人技术仍然需要几年的时间。
阿尔卡迪的愿景处于完全不同的层面。

posts.name: 硅谷投研手记
posts.text:
硅谷投研手记
@Kunka020
关注
$NVDA 这份财报，数字层面没什么好说的——$681亿收入beat，Q1指引$780亿再beat 7%。市场已经习惯了。
我想聊三个大家没怎么讨论的点：
1/ 毛利率75.2%才是这份财报最重要的数字
Blackwell从去年Q3开始量产爬坡，按常理新架构初期良率低、成本高，毛利率应该承压。但75.2%不仅没掉，还比上季度稳住了。这说明台积电CoWoS和Amkor的先进封装良率爬坡速度远超预期。对整个封装产业链来说，这是个被低估的信号。
2/ “不包含任何中国数据中心计算收入”
Q1指引$780亿，管理层特意强调这个数字不含中国。也就是说，如果出口管制有任何松动，这$780亿还有上行空间。反过来想——一家公司砍掉了全球第二大市场，收入还能+73%，这本身就说明非中国市场的AI算力需求有多疑狂。
3/ 推理经济学正在重塑NVDA的护城河
Jensen说Grace Blackwell是“the king of inference”。这句话的含义比表面深得多。训练市场的天花板是可见的——全球就那么几个大模型要训。但推理市场是跟着应用走的，每一个AI agent、每一次API调用都在消耗推理算力。Agentic AI意味着推理需求是训练的10-100倍。NVDA从卖训练卡变成卖推理基础设施，TAM直接扩了一个数量级。
盘后没涨，市场觉得“符合预期”。但我觉得市场还没完全price in推理侧的结构性变化。
上午7:28 · 2026年2月26日
·

 查看

Jensen说Grace Blackwell是“the king of inference”。这句话的含义比表面深得多。训练市场的天花板是可见的——全球就那么几个大模型要训。但推理市场是跟着应用走的，每一个AI agent、每一次API调用都在消耗推理算力。Agentic AI意味着推理需求是训练的10-100倍。NVDA从卖训练卡变成卖推理基础设施，TAM直接扩了一个数量级。
盘后没涨，市场觉得“符合预期”。但我觉得市场还没完全price in推理侧的结构性变化。

关注
According to NHTSA data and trackers like 
http://
tesladeaths.com (updated Nov 2025), 2 fatalities have been confirmed where Tesla FSD was engaged (out of ~65 total Autopilot-related deaths across all Tesla crashes).
Tesla's latest FSD safety report (Q4 2025 data) shows 1 major collision per 5.3M miles driven with FSD—8x better than the US average of 1 per 660k miles, based on billions of supervised miles. FSD remains Level 2 supervised; driver attention required. No new FSD-specific fatality reports in early 2026 filings.

Tesla Deaths: Digital record of Tesla crashes resulting in death
Tesla Deaths is a record of Tesla accidents that involved the death of a driver, occupant, cyclist, motorcyclist, or pedestrian.

Tesla 最新的 FSD 安全报告（2025 年第四季度数据）显示，使用 FSD 行驶每 530 万英里就会发生 1 起重大碰撞事故，这比美国平均每 66 万英里发生 1 起碰撞事故（基于数十亿监管里程）高出 8 倍。 FSD 仍保持 2 级监管；需要驾驶员注意。 2026 年初提交的文件中没有新的 FSD 特定死亡报告。
